'''Enrique Martín Morales'''{{efn|{{IPA-es|enˈɾike maɾˈtin moˈɾales}}}} (born December 24, 1971), known professionally as '''Ricky Martin''', is a Puerto Rican singer, songwriter, and actor. He is known for his musical versatility, as his [[Ricky Martin albums discography|discography]] spans multiple genres, including [[Latin pop]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[Dance music|dance]], [[reggaeton]], and [[Salsa music|salsa]].<!-- Sourced in "Musical styles and themes" section --> Dubbed the "[[Honorific nicknames in popular music#M|King of Latin Pop]]", the "King of Latin Music", and the "Latin Pop God", he is regarded as one of the most influential artists in the world.<!-- Sourced in "Legacy and influence" section --> Born in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], Martin began appearing in television commercials at the age of 9 and began his musical career at age 12, as a member of Puerto Rican boy band [[Menudo (group)|Menudo]]. He started his solo career in 1991 while in [[Sony Music Mexico]], gaining recognition in Latin America with the release of his first two studio albums, ''[[Ricky Martin (1991 album)|Ricky Martin]]'' (1991) and ''[[Me Amaras (album)|Me Amaras]]'' (1993), both of which were focused on [[Sentimental ballad|ballads]].

Martin's third album, ''[[A Medio Vivir]]'' (1995), helped him rise to prominence in European countries. The chart-topping single "[[María (Ricky Martin song)|María]]", incorporated a mixture of [[Latin music]] genres and became his first international hit. His international success was further solidified with his fourth album, ''[[Vuelve (album)|Vuelve]]'' (1998). The album, which earned Martin his first [[Grammy Awards|Grammy Award]], spawned chart-topping hits "[[Vuelve (Ricky Martin song)|Vuelve]]" and "[[The Cup of Life|La Copa de la Vida]]". Martin performed the latter at the [[41st Annual Grammy Awards]], which was greeted with a massive standing ovation and is known as a game-changer for Latin music worldwide. His first English album, ''[[Ricky Martin (1999 album)|Ricky Martin]]'' (1999) became his first US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] number one. The [[lead single]] "[[Livin' la Vida Loca]]" is considered to be Martin's biggest hit, topping both the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and the [[UK Singles Chart]]. Martin's success in the late '90s is generally seen as the beginning of the "Latin explosion". He has been credited for getting Latin pop music genre to mainstream recognition, paving the way for a large number of Latin artists to achieve global success.

Martin has since established his status as a [[sex symbol]] and a [[pop icon]], releasing several successful albums, including [[List of best-selling Latin albums|all-time Latin bestsellers]] ''[[Almas del Silencio]]'' (2003) and ''[[MTV Unplugged (Ricky Martin album)|MTV Unplugged]]'' (2006), as well as Grammy Award winner ''[[A Quien Quiera Escuchar]]'' (2015). He has also amassed many successful singles and chart-topper hits, including "[[She Bangs]]", "[[Nobody Wants to Be Lonely]]", "[[Tal Vez]]", "[[Tu Recuerdo (Ricky Martin song)|Tu Recuerdo]]", "[[La Mordidita]]", "[[Vente Pa' Ca]]", and "[[Canción Bonita]]". As an actor, Martin gained popularity and stardom for his role in the hit [[soap opera]] ''[[General Hospital]]'' (1994-1996), while his portrayal of [[Antonio D'Amico]] in ''[[The Assassination of Gianni Versace: American Crime Story]]'' (2018) marked the acting opportunity of his career, garnering him an [[Emmy Awards|Emmy]] nomination. He also starred as [[Che Guevara in popular culture#In theater|Ché]] in the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] revival of the musical ''[[Evita (musical)|Evita]]'' in 2012, which broke the theatre's box-office sales record seven times.

Having sold over 70 million records worldwide, Martin is one of the best-selling Latin music artists of all time. He has scored 11 ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Latin Songs]] number-one songs, and won over 200 awards (most awarded male Latin artist), including two Grammy Awards, five [[Latin Grammy Awards]], five [[MTV Video Music Awards]] (tied for most wins by a Latin artist), two [[American Music Awards]], three [[Latin American Music Awards]], three [[Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], nine [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]], eight [[World Music Awards]], fourteen [[Lo Nuestro Awards]], a ''[[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Record]]'', and a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]. He is ranked among the Greatest Latin Artists of All Time, the Greatest Music Video Artists of All Time, and the Most Influential Latin Artists of All Time by ''Billboard''. His philanthropy and activism focus on [[LGBT rights by country or territory|LGBT rights]] and fighting against [[human trafficking]]; in 2004, he founded The Ricky Martin Foundation, a non-profit, non-governmental organization that focuses on denouncing human trafficking and educating about the crime's existence.

== Early life and career ==
[[File:San Juan, Puerto Rico (2529298606).jpg|thumb|left|Martin was born in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]].]]
Enrique Martín Morales was born on December 24, 1971, in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/pop-stars-real-names/|title=Pop Stars' Real Names|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=June 26, 2014|access-date=November 27, 2021|archive-date=November 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211127091717/https://www.billboard.com/photos/pop-stars-real-names/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/ricky-martin-reveals-hes-gay-20100330-r92b.html|title=Ricky Martin reveals he's gay|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=March 30, 2010|access-date=November 27, 2021|archive-date=November 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211127092507/https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/ricky-martin-reveals-hes-gay-20100330-r92b.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="NBC PR">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/national-puerto-rico-day-parade-brings-generations-boricuas-together-n1015521|title=National Puerto Rico Day Parade brings generations of boricuas together|publisher=[[NBC News]]|last=Aviles|first=Gwen|date=June 9, 2019|access-date=November 27, 2021|archive-date=November 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211127092624/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/national-puerto-rico-day-parade-brings-generations-boricuas-together-n1015521|url-status=live}}</ref> His mother, Doña Nereida Morales, is a former accountant; his father, Enrique Martín Negroni, is a former psychologist who previously worked as a regional supervisor for a Puerto Rican mental-health agency.<ref name="TheThings Facts">{{cite news|url=https://www.thethings.com/ricky-martin-secrets-singer-coming-out-puerto-rican/|title=Things You Probably Didn't Know About Ricky Martin|work=TheThings|last=Filart|first=Matt|date=May 24, 2020|access-date=November 27, 2021|archive-date=November 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211127094757/https://www.thethings.com/ricky-martin-secrets-singer-coming-out-puerto-rican/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hola.com/us/celebrities/20200610fo942ppzqq/ricky-martin-jwan-yosef-marriage-problems-1/|title=Ricky Martin opens up about the issues he faced with husband Jwan Yosef following the birth of their daughter|work=[[¡Hola!]]|date=June 10, 2020|access-date=November 27, 2021|archive-date=November 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211127095301/https://www.hola.com/us/celebrities/20200610fo942ppzqq/ricky-martin-jwan-yosef-marriage-problems-1/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="People Favorite">{{cite news|url=https://people.com/archive/cover-story-my-favorite-martin-vol-51-no-24/|title=My Favorite Martin|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|last=Schneider|first=Karen S.|date=June 28, 1999|access-date=November 27, 2021|archive-date=November 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211127103226/https://people.com/archive/cover-story-my-favorite-martin-vol-51-no-24/|url-status=live}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was two years old, and although his mother had [[Child custody|custody]] of Martin, he could also move freely between his father's house in the middle-class suburb of University Gardens in San Juan, and his paternal grandmother's house nearby. In an interview with ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', he told the magazine that he "never had to make decisions" about who he loved more, and he was "always happy". Martin has two older maternal half-brothers, Fernando and Ángel Fernández, two younger paternal half-brothers, Eric and Daniel Martín, and a younger paternal half-sister, Vanessa Martín.<ref name="People Favorite"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.es/estilo/gente/abci-resuelto-misterio-hermano-desaparecido-ricky-martin-201710062017_noticia.html|title=Resuelto el misterio del hermano desaparecido de Ricky Martin|work=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=es|last=Mellado|first=Ana|date=September 10, 2017|access-date=November 27, 2021|archive-date=November 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211127103621/https://www.abc.es/estilo/gente/abci-resuelto-misterio-hermano-desaparecido-ricky-martin-201710062017_noticia.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Martin has [[Spaniards|Spanish]] heritage of [[Basques|Basque]] and [[Canary Islanders|Canarian]] descent. As he explained to ''[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]'', the Martins traveled from Spain to Puerto Rico in 1779.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.es/cultura/musica/abci-ricky-martin-nunca-abierto-respecto-sentimientos-como-ahora-201609160149_noticia_amp.html|title=Ricky Martin: 'Nunca fui tan abierto con respecto a mis sentimientos como ahora'|work=ABC|language=es|last=Pita|first=Pablo Martínez|date=September 16, 2017|access-date=November 27, 2021|archive-date=November 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211127151750/https://www.abc.es/cultura/musica/abci-ricky-martin-nunca-abierto-respecto-sentimientos-como-ahora-201609160149_noticia_amp.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He also has some [[Corsicans|Corsican]] origin through his paternal grandmother.<ref name="rickybook">{{Cite book|title=Me|last=Martin|first=Ricky|publisher=Celebra|pages=9, 16, 17, 18, 21, 24, 25, 28, 30, 31, 32, 36, 37, 46, 48, 50, 55, 57, 59, 60, 61, 65, 76, 77, 78, 79, 80, 81, 89, 90, 94, 103, 104, 108, 109, 111, 145, 243|year=2010|isbn=9780451234438}}</ref>

Martin grew up [[Catholicity|Catholic]]. The people closest to him called him "Kiki" (a nickname that comes from Enrique). He began singing at age six, using wooden kitchen spoons as make-believe microphones; he often sang songs by Puerto Rican boy band [[Menudo (group)|Menudo]], as well as English-language [[Rock music|rock]] groups such as [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Journey (band)|Journey]], and [[REO Speedwagon]]. His mother's side of the family was musically inclined and his maternal grandfather was a poet. Martin later reflected on his time spent with his family as a child: "Every time I find myself in front of an audience, be it twenty people or one hundred thousand, once again I feel the energy that consumed me back at the family gatherings of my youth." He attended Colegio Sagrado Corazón, a bilingual Catholic grade school in University Gardens since fourth grade and was an "average" student there. When he was nine years old, he began appearing in television commercials for products such as soft drinks, toothpaste, and fast food restaurants, most notably [[Crush (soft drink)|Orange Crush]] and [[Burger King]]. In a year and a half, he starred in 11 commercials.<ref name="People Favorite"/><ref name="rickybook"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.out.com/celebs/2020/12/15/ricky-martins-first-professional-gig-was-soda-commercial|title=Ricky Martin's First Professional Gig Was This Soda Commercial|work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]|last=Street|first=Mikelle|date=December 15, 2020|access-date=November 27, 2021|archive-date=November 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211127164623/https://www.out.com/celebs/2020/12/15/ricky-martins-first-professional-gig-was-soda-commercial|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Career==
=== 1983–1989: Menudo ===
{{see also|Menudo (group)|l1=Menudo}}
{{Listen
| filename    = Menudo - Rayo de Luna.ogg
| title       = "Rayo de Luna"
| description = Martin made his recording debut on the song "Rayo de Luna", from Menudo's 1984 album, ''[[Evolución (Menudo album)|Evolución]]''.
| format      = [[Ogg]]
