}}

As a child, Martin used to sing songs by Menudo and American rock bands such as Led Zeppelin, Journey, and REO Speedwagon, which were what his "older siblings were listening to at the time". While Martin and his brothers spent their time listening to classic rock, their mother would interrupt them to make them listen to Latin music. She brought him CDs of [[Fania All-Stars]], [[Celia Cruz]], [[El Gran Combo de Puerto Rico]], and [[Gilberto Santa Rosa]] that slowly made him appreciate the richness of Puerto Rican culture. Also, she once took them to a Fania All-Stars concert, which Martin is "beyond grateful" for it. He expresses that thanks to her mother, those influences had a "profound effect" on his musical career.<ref name="rickybook"/> Martin has also cited [[Elvis Presley]], [[the Beatles]], [[Michael Jackson]], and [[Madonna]] for teaching him "the beauty of pop".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/1999/sep/11/tvandradio.television|title=MTV video awards Grammy winner Lauryn Hill dominates|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Gregoriadis|first=Linus|date=September 10, 1999|access-date=January 16, 2022}}</ref> He stated about Madonna: "I was very influenced by her and her music. I know every choreography of Madonna."<ref name="Document Journal">{{cite news|url=https://www.documentjournal.com/2020/12/ricky-martin-and-berlutis-kris-van-assche-reflect-on-two-decades-of-radical-self-expression/|title=Ricky Martin and Berluti's Kris Van Assche reflect on two decades of radical self expression|work=[[Document Journal]]|last=Hicklin|first=Aaron|date=December 7, 2020|access-date=January 16, 2022}}</ref> Additionally, he mentions [[Carlos Santana]], [[José Feliciano]], Celia Cruz, and [[Gloria Estefan]] as the artists who paved the way for him,<ref name="EW protests">{{cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/music/2019/10/29/ricky-martin-puerto-rico-protests-influenced-new-album-teases-release-date/|title=Ricky Martin says protests in Puerto Rico influenced his new album, teases release date|last=Cordero|first=Rosy|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=February 27, 2021|date=October 29, 2019}}</ref> naming Feliciano as one of the people who inspired him when he was a teenager: "I was always fascinated with his music."<ref name="Document Journal"/> In addition to the musical influences, Martin is inspired by [[David Bowie]]'s "ambiguous sexuality".<ref name="Hommes">{{cite news|url=https://www.lofficielitalia.com/uomo/intervista-ricky-martin-the-now-icon-popstar-internazionale-vita-privata#|title=The Now Icon: Ricky Martin|last=Croci|first=Roberto|work=[[L'Officiel Hommes]]|access-date=March 11, 2021|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> While growing up, he used to ask himself if he wanted to be like the openly gay singer [[Elton John]] or he just liked him, admiring his music, colors, and wigs.<ref name="Variety Come out">{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/ricky-martin-gay-comung-out-1234704837/|title=Ricky Martin on the Moment He Decided to Come Out as Gay: 'I've Been Super Happy Ever Since'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Malkin|first=Marc|date=July 13, 2020|access-date=January 17, 2022}}</ref> He has also cited [[Barbra Streisand]] as an entertainer he wants to be like: "I want to be an entertainer, not just a singer."<ref>{{cite news|title=Menudo|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/101773390/daily-press/|newspaper=[[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]|date=December 21, 1995|page=40|via=Newspapers.com|access-date=May 13, 2022}}</ref>

=== Musical styles and themes ===
Considered to be a versatile artist,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://los40.com.pa/los40/2007/08/13/actualidad/1186991400_466104.html|title=Ricky Martin.|publisher=[[Los 40]]|language=es|date=August 13, 2007|access-date=January 17, 2022|archive-date=January 17, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220117130856/https://los40.com.pa/los40/2007/08/13/actualidad/1186991400_466104.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://exafm.com/noticias/general/kanye-west-fue-visto-en-la-celebracion-del-cumpleanos-de-su-hija-chicago-se-reencuentra-con-las-kardashian/|title=¿Por qué tenemos dos papás? Preguntaron los hijos de Ricky Martin|publisher=[[XHEXA-FM]]|language=es|date=January 15, 2018|access-date=January 17, 2022|archive-date=January 17, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220117130845/https://exafm.com/noticias/general/kanye-west-fue-visto-en-la-celebracion-del-cumpleanos-de-su-hija-chicago-se-reencuentra-con-las-kardashian/|url-status=live}}</ref> Martin describes his music as [[Latin pop]], saying: "When you say 'Latin pop', the spectrum is so broad, It's inevitable to not be influenced by everything that’s happening in the industry, but always keeping your identity firm by knowing who you are."<ref name="EW protests"/> He has also described his music as fusion, while noting that he does not "ride the waves that are in fashion at the moment".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.oprahdaily.com/entertainment/a32908634/ricky-martin-quarantine-pausa-interview/|title=Ricky Martin Reveals How His New EP, Pausa Helped Him Overcome Quarantine Anxiety|work=[[O, The Oprah Magazine]]|last=Davis|first=Arianna|date=June 18, 2020|access-date=January 17, 2022|archive-date=January 17, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220117141048/https://www.oprahdaily.com/entertainment/a32908634/ricky-martin-quarantine-pausa-interview/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Metro music">{{cite news|url=https://www.metro.pr/pr/entretenimiento/2020/01/02/ricky-martin-musicaliza-activismo-politico-social.html|title=Ricky Martin musicaliza su activismo político y social|work=[[Metro International|Metro Puerto Rico]]|language=es|last=Túa|first=Lynet Santiago|date=January 2, 2020|access-date=January 17, 2022|archive-date=January 17, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220117141057/https://www.metro.pr/pr/entretenimiento/2020/01/02/ricky-martin-musicaliza-activismo-politico-social.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Music critics have described his songs as Latin pop, pop, dance, ballad, reggaeton, Latin, African, rock, [[salsa music|salsa]], [[flamenco]], [[Urban contemporary|urban]], [[samba]], [[cumbia]], [[Merengue music|merengue]], [[Cuban rumba|rumba]], [[Funk|Latin funk]], [[Bomba (Puerto Rico)|bomba]], [[batucada]], [[vallenato]], [[dancehall]], [[Mambo (music)|mambo]], [[Europop]], [[house music|house]], [[disco]], [[Electronic dance music|EDM]], [[dance-pop]], [[Electro (music)|electro]], [[techno]], [[dubstep]], [[world music]], [[Middle Eastern music|Middle Eastern]], [[folk-pop]], [[bossa nova]], [[pop rock]], [[Sunshine pop|soft pop]], [[soft rock]], [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]], [[gospel music|gospel]], [[jazz]], [[Trap music|trap]], [[Latin hip hop|hip hop]], [[doo-wop]], [[ska]], and [[Rock and roll|rock' n' roll]].<ref>Citations regarding Martin songs' genres and styles:
